&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; Can you have a look at the logic I have implemented here:
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; /afs/cern.ch/user/b/benitezj/public/TriggerObjectFactory.cc
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; where I loop only once over the input trigger object list and the duplicate objects get removed by a deltaR and deltaPt cut.
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; I tested this logic to give the same trigger matching as before the duplicate removal.
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; I noted also that the number of objects that pass this logic is larger (avg=23) than with the previous code (avg=18), so it seems that some additional objects are being removed by the previous algorithm.
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; 
&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt;&gt; I'm definitely not happy with this. Our use of equality is well defined and documented. It shouldn't be broken here. The duplicates are really the exact same object read out of the same collection. They must be equal not just nearly equal. The point of using deltaR matching is when objects are si

